  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Developments\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, US)\n- First international anti-money laundering guidelines\n- Initial focus on financial reporting and suspicious transaction monitoring\n\n2. Key Milestones\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) establishment in 1989\n- Basel Committee recommendations\n- United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)\n\n3. Modern Regulatory Approaches\n- Enhanced customer due diligence requirements\n- Mandatory beneficial ownership reporting\n- Stricter Know Your Customer (KYC) protocols\n- Increased cross-border information sharing\n- Expanded cryptocurrency transaction regulations\n\n4. Technological Adaptations\n- Advanced digital monitoring systems\n- Machine learning-based transaction analysis\n- Real-time suspicious activity detection\n- Blockchain tracking mechanisms\n\n5. Comprehensive Legal Frameworks\n- Expanded definition of money laundering\n- Increased penalties and criminal prosecution\n- International cooperation mechanisms\n- Sector-specific compliance requirements\n\n6. Recent Trends\n- Cryptocurrency regulation\n- Enhanced digital financial transparency\n- Greater emphasis on preventing terrorist financing\n- Continuous regulatory updates\n\nThe legislative landscape continues to evolve, addressing emerging financial technologies and sophisticated laundering techniques.",
